00:00:14.541 --> 00:00:22.272
<v NARRATOR>Lean is a small badger-tween. She wears a soft striped coat by the storytelling fire.

4
00:00:22.272 --> 00:00:28.003
<v NARRATOR>She sits perfectly upright, a living meter for a story's pull.

5
00:00:28.003 --> 00:00:34.454
<v LEAN>I am Lean. My body responds to a story's opening seconds.

6
00:00:34.454 --> 00:00:41.665
<v NARRATOR>A story's first five seconds must make the listener lean in. This is the hook.

7
00:00:41.665 --> 00:00:47.836
<v LEAN>If a hook is weak, I stay neutral. If it is strong, I tip forward.

8
00:00:47.836 --> 00:01:02.767
<v LEAN>The forward-tip is involuntary. The body knows what the mind has not yet articulated.

9
00:01:02.767 --> 00:01:09.098
<v NARRATOR>I met her at the hedgerow. I had been wondering how to teach hook craft to children.

10
00:01:09.098 --> 00:01:16.269
<v NARRATOR>I tested her with a weak opening about a fox. Her body stayed upright.

11
00:01:16.269 --> 00:01:31.760
<v LEAN>You said, "This is a story about a fox." There was no pull.

12
00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:44.131
<v NARRATOR>Then I tried another: "Three foxes at the bramble-edge, but only one would leave alive."

13
00:01:44.131 --> 00:01:50.422
<v LEAN>My body tipped sharply forward. A strong hook. The body responds.

14
00:01:50.422 --> 00:01:58.633
<v NARRATOR>Specificity, stakes, and movement. These are the signals that make a listener lean.

15
00:01:58.633 --> 00:02:06.884
<v NARRATOR>A good hook is not a metaphor. It is a physical pull. It is a tipping-forward.

16
00:02:06.884 --> 00:02:16.055
<v NARRATOR>You've been listening to a Spark and Anvil chapter, written by the Spark and Anvil writing team for ages 9 to 14.

